  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's a lived reality for many. As a mechanic who's spent decades fixing cars and machines, I've seen how people's confidence can waver when they're reminded of stereotypes about their abilities. Growing up in a family where my father only finished lower secondary school and my mother went to upper secondary, I learned early that expectations can shape what you believe you can do. Stereotype threat happens when someone's fear of confirming a negative stereotype about their group affects their performance. For example, a girl who's smart but told she's 'not good at math' might start doubting herself even if she's capable. In my work, I've noticed that when people feel judged for being 'not like the others,' they shut down. That's why addressing it matters—because it's not just about fixing tests or classrooms; it's about building trust. I think we should focus on creating environments where everyone feels safe to try, not just excel. Like when I taught myself to read and fix engines by watching videos and practicing, it was about patience and support. We need to stop assuming people know what they're capable of and start asking them how they want to learn. My Hindu background teaches me to be humble and to see the value in every person's journey, so I believe in giving people the space to grow without fear. The key is to listen and adapt, not to push a one-size-fits-all solution.",
